<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-068-418  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 068 418.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Feb 21 1989 v3 n8 p18(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Micro Dynamics firms up its Mac archiving systems. (MARS -Multi-user Archival and Retrieval System) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Perrow, Jonathan.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Micro Dynamics Ltd. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Multiuser Archival and Retrieval System (Information retrievalsystem).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionDocument Management SystemsInformation Storage and Retrieval.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Micro Dynamics firms up its Mac archiving systemsandM;Silver Spring, Md.andP;  -- Concentrating its attack on a corporate and federal&quot;paper blizzard,&quot; Micro Dynamics has consolidated its product line into threeMac-based document archiving systems.andM;Micro Dynamics was one of the first companies to champion the Macintosh inthe field of document management, an electronic alternative to microfilm orpaper filing designed primarily for use at law offices, federal agencies andFortune 1,000 companies.andM;Micro Dynamics' MARS (Multi-user Archival and Retrieval System) consists of aMac platform running Micro Dynamics' own software and linked to optical WORM(write once, read many) storage.andP;  Fujitsu scanners, and AppleTalk or Ethernetnetworks.andP;  Options include optical character recognition(OCR) hardware,eight- and 24-bit color interface cards, and color or monochrome monitors.andO;Systems are already in use at the National Institute of Health of Bethesda,Md., Arthur Young andamp; Co. in New York and elsewhere.andM;&quot;MARS has really simplified the process,&quot; said Paul Gussenhoven, officemanager of the legal department at Arthur Young, where the Micro Dynamicssystem has replaced microfilm.andP;  &quot;Once the legal documents are all on a WORMdrive, a lawyer can pick out the subset of documents that pertain to aparticular case, batch them together and send them to the printer.&quot;andM;MARS now comes in three configurations:andM;* Series 1000, a basic system designed for up to ten users ranging in pricefrom $45,000 to $120,000.andM;* Series 3000, an enhanced system designed for up to 20 users and ranging inprice from $95,000 to $275,000.andM;* Series 5000, a high-end system for up to 100 users, costing between$250,000 and $1.2 million.andM;Micro Dynamics is located at 8555 16th St., Suite 802, Silver Spring, Md.andO;20910; (301) 589-6300.andO;</TEXT></DOC>